Take-home Exercise 1: Application of Spatial Point Pattern Analysis on Grab Hailing Service in Singapore

Author

Tang Xin Yi

Published

January 17, 2024

1 Problem context

This exercise is looking into discovering insights relevant to the geographical and spatial distribution of Grab hailing service locations in Singapore.

In this exercise, the following packages are used.

Show the code 
pacman::p_load(sf, tidyverse, tmap, spatstat, raster, maptools, spNetwork, classInt, viridis, arrow, lubridate)

2 Data

2.1 Background of the datasets used

The following datasets are used in this analysis exercise.

  • GrabPosisi: Aspatial data

  • RoadMap: from OpenStreetMap

  • Master Plan 2019 Subzone Boundary (No Sea) from Data.gov.sg

2.3 Prepare required Geographical data layers

This exercise needs the following geographical data layers

  1. Grab taxi location points either by origins or destinations

  2. Road layer within Singapore excluding outer islands

  3. Singapore boundary layer excluding outer islands

2.3.1 Get Grab taxi origin and destination layer

Get the origin tibble data.frame

Show the code 
trip_origin <- grab %>% 
  # group by trip id
  group_by(trj_id) %>% 
  # sort: ascending by default
  arrange(pingtimestamp, .by_group = FALSE) %>% 
  # get 1st row
  filter(row_number()==1) %>% 
  mutate(weekday = wday(pingtimestamp,
                        label = TRUE,
                        abbr = TRUE),
         start_hr = factor(hour(pingtimestamp)),
         day = factor(mday(pingtimestamp)))

Get the destination tibble data.frame

Converting rawlat and rawlng with formula provided in this StackOverflow tread

Show the code 
trip_dest <- grab %>% 
  group_by(trj_id) %>% 
  arrange(desc(pingtimestamp), .by_group = FALSE) %>% 
  filter(row_number()==1) %>% 
  mutate(weekday = wday(pingtimestamp,
                        label = TRUE,
                        abbr = TRUE),
         end_hr = factor(hour(pingtimestamp)),
         day = factor(mday(pingtimestamp)))

The extracted data layers are written into rds files for easier reference later.

Show the code 
write_rds(trip_origin, "../../data/rds/trip_origin.rds")
write_rds(trip_dest, "../../data/rds/trip_dest.rds")

According to the steps in In-class Exercises 3, the tibble needs to be wrangled.

3.1 Geospatial data wrangling

sf is preferred, convert to sf

Upon investigation, the window size of the trip_origin and sg_boun differs too much.

With reference to this page, the lat-long values are converted into SVY21 XY coordinates.

Show the code 
class(trip_origin)
[1] "grouped_df" "tbl_df"     "tbl"        "data.frame"
Show the code 
class(trip_dest)
[1] "grouped_df" "tbl_df"     "tbl"        "data.frame"
Show the code 
class(sg_boun)
[1] "sfc_MULTIPOLYGON" "sfc"
Show the code 
# setting existing coordinate as lat-long system
trip_origin_sp_dec <- SpatialPoints(coords = cbind(trip_origin$rawlng, trip_origin$rawlat),
                                    proj4string = CRS("+proj=longlat"))
trip_origin_sp_svy <- spTransform(trip_origin_sp_dec,
                                  CRS("+init=epsg:3414"))
Warning in CPL_crs_from_input(x): GDAL Message 1: +init=epsg:XXXX syntax is
deprecated. It might return a CRS with a non-EPSG compliant axis order.
Show the code 
trip_dest_sp_dec <- SpatialPoints(coords = cbind(trip_dest$rawlng, trip_dest$rawlat), 
                                  proj4string = CRS("+proj=longlat"))
trip_dest_sp_svy <- spTransform(trip_dest_sp_dec,
                                CRS("+init=epsg:3414"))

3.2 Calculation

Auto bandwidth with different kernel function for trip_origin

Show the code 
kde_trip_originSG_G <- density(trip_originSG_ppp,
                                sigma = bw.diggle,
                                edge = TRUE,
                                kernel = "gaussian")
plot(kde_trip_originSG_G)
Show the code 
kde_trip_originSG_Q <- density(trip_originSG_ppp,
                                sigma = bw.diggle,
                                edge = TRUE,
                                kernel = "quartic")

plot(kde_trip_originSG_Q)
